    <p>If your score is 715 (the national average), you are at or above approximately 50 percent of all U.S. consumers. If your score is 740 or above, you are in the top 49 percent. And if you have achieved an 800 or higher, you are in the top 23 percent of credit users in the country.</p>

    <h2>How Different Life Events Affect Your Credit Score</h2>
    <p>Certain life events can have dramatic impacts on your credit score. Understanding these in advance helps you prepare and minimize damage.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buying a home:</strong> The mortgage application process involves a hard inquiry (minus 5 to 10 points) and opening a large new account (temporary dip of 15 to 40 points). However, over time, a mortgage with consistent payments will strengthen your credit profile significantly.</li>
      <li><strong>Getting married:</strong> Marriage itself does not affect your credit score — scores remain individual. However, joint accounts opened after marriage will appear on both spouses' credit reports, and one partner's financial behavior can now affect the other's score through those shared accounts.</li>
      <li><strong>Divorce:</strong> Divorce can devastate credit scores if joint accounts are not handled properly. Missed payments on joint accounts during divorce proceedings affect both parties. Close or refinance joint accounts as soon as possible during a divorce.</li>
      <li><strong>Job loss:</strong> Losing your job does not directly affect your score (employment is not a scoring factor), but the financial strain of unemployment often leads to missed payments and increased credit card usage, both of which damage your score. If you anticipate difficulty making payments, contact your creditors proactively — many offer hardship programs.</li>
      <li><strong>Medical debt:</strong> As of 2023, the three major credit bureaus no longer include medical debt under 500 on credit reports, and paid medical collections are removed immediately. This was a significant change that helped millions of Americans with medical debt improve their credit scores.</li>
    </ul>

